Stabilization in model with twisted moduli 

Twisted moduli 

Twisted moduli fields  are localized 
at orbifold fixed points and these 
moduli fields are important from several phenomenological 
view points in 4D models obtained from type I 
and type II orientifold models.
For example, the gauge kinetic functions 
corresponding to gauge groups originated from  branes 
are written as
 
where  is a model-dependent 
constant.
Concerned about , here we take purely phenomenological 
standpoint, that is, we treat  as free parameters.  
Similarly, for the gauge groups originated from e.g. 
-branes, which are wrapped on the -th torus (), 
the corresponding gauge kinetic functions are written as 
 
where  is the moduli field corresponding to the
-th torus and its Kahler potential is obtained 
 
that is, its form is exactly the same as the Kahler potential of 
the dilaton field ().
Thus, we can discuss the stabilization of  due to 
gaugino condensation from -originated gauge groups in the same way 
as the stabilization of  due to condensation from 
 gaugino fields.
Here, we concentrate ourselves on the  stabilization.


One of important aspects is that 
the twisted moduli field  plays a role in 
4D Green-Schwarz anomaly cancellation mechanism.
For example, under anomalous  symmetry, 
the twisted moduli fields are assumed to transform at one-loop level
 
with the transformation parameter .
The Fayet-Iliopoulos  term 
is written by the first derivative of Kahler potential 

,

where  is the Kahler potential of 
the twisted moduli field.
Thus, the magnitude of the Fayet-Iliopoulos  term is 
determined by the VEV of .


