Assuming the Kahler potential 
 and , 
we have shown that the VEV of  can be stabilized 
with the VEV of  fixed.
The former case implies that the canonical Kahler potential 
is important for the stabilization of the twisted moduli.
Such analysis can be extended into the case with 
polynomial Kahler potential .
On the other hand, the latter case with 
 shows that even 
with the logarithmic Kahler potential, the positive 
exponent in the non-perturbative superpotential is 
useful to stabilize the VEV of twisted moduli fields.
It is speculative whether really 
 for large , but that is 
an example of Kahler potentials which have the behavior 
opposite to the canonical form at large .
For other forms of Kahler potential, the analysis can be 
extended.
The key-point in the stabilization of twisted moduli is that 
the polynomial form of Kahler potential is useful and 
the positive exponent of  in the superpotential is 
helpful.
These aspects differ from the dilaton stabilization.
The positive exponent of the dilaton field in the 
non-perturbative superpotential corresponds to the 
asymptotically non-free case (See Ref.  
for the dilaton
stabilization in the asymptotically non-free case.) .



